Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Statutory Offences – Road Traffic Act

\[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9150/2022/01.\]

12 September 2022

### District Judge Salina Bte Ishak:

## Background

1       The accused, Mr Lim Eng Ann, a 53-year-old male Singapore citizen had pleaded guilty to the following amended charge:

Amended Charge

> are charged that you, on 8 July 2020, at about 3.02 p.m., along Yishun Ring Road towards Yishun Avenue 2 Lamp Post 4F, Singapore, did drive motor taxi SHD4787X, on a road without due care and attention, to wit, by failing to keep a proper lookout ahead and collided into one Ahmad Bin Mamud, a 71-year old male pedestrian at the material time) who was crossing on the road from your right to left and hurt was caused to the said Ahmad Bin Mamud, by such driving, and you have thereby committed an offence under Section 65(1)(a) of the Road Traffic Act, Chapter 276 punishable under Section 65(4)(a) of the Road Traffic Act, Chapter 276.

2       The accused was originally charged with an offence of driving without due care and attention and causing grievous hurt to a pedestrian, one Ahmad Bin Mamud under s 65(3)(_a_) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”). On condition of a plea of guilt, the Prosecution agreed to proceed on a reduced charge of driving without due care and attention and causing hurt under s 65(4)(_a_) of the RTA.

3       On 16 August 2022, the accused pleaded guilty to the amended charge (C1A) and admitted to the Statement of Facts without any qualification. After carefully considering the Prosecution’s submissions on sentence and the accused’s plea in mitigation, I imposed a fine of $2,000 and disqualified him from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of 15 months with effect from 16 August 2022.

4       The accused being dissatisfied with my decision had filed his Notice of Appeal against my sentence and order of disqualification on 17 August 2022. He has paid his fine in full on 16 August 2022.

5       Having set out the background for the present case, I now provide the reasons for my decision.

## Salient Facts

6       The accused was the driver of motor taxi bearing registration number SHD4787X during the time of the incident. The victim is Ahmad Bin Mamud, a 71-year-old Singaporean male at the material time. He was a pedestrian during the time of the incident.

7       On 8 July 2020, at about 3.02pm, the accused was driving his motor taxi out from a car park in the vicinity of Yishun Ring Road. As the accused was exiting the carpark located opposite of Block 239 Yishun Ring Road, he initially stopped at the stop line. The victim can be seen standing on the accused’s right side and the victim was waiting in the middle of the road.

![](data:image;base64,)

8       When the traffic was clear for a right turn, the accused proceeded to make a right turn while the victim started to walk towards Block 239 Yishun Ring Road. Along Yishun Ring Road towards Yishun Avenue 2 Lamp Post 4F, Singapore, the accused collided onto the victim’s left and the impact caused the victim’s head and body to hit the bonnet and the victim fell to the ground. Upon collision, the accused promptly got out of his car and immediately rendered assistance to the victim. The accused drove without due care and attention by failing to keep a proper lookout ahead and collided into the victim, who was crossing on the road from the accused’s right to left and hurt was caused to the victim by such driving. The incident was captured on the in-vehicle camera footage from the accused’s said motor taxi.

9       There were no visible or fresh damage found on the accused’s motor-taxi.

#### Injury

10     The victim was conscious and conveyed to Khoo Teck Puat Hospital by ambulance. On examination, the victim had significant left hip pain and was unable to access right hip range of motion. He had some mild tenderness over left femur shaft and his left knee range of motion was unable to be accessed due to hip pain. He was diagnosed with left hip intertrochanteric fracture and left knee tibia plateau fracture. He subsequently underwent surgical fixation of his left hip on 11 July 2020 and surgical fixation of left proximal tibia on 15 July 2020.

11     The victim was hospitalised for 15 days from 8 July 2020 to 23 July 2020 and subsequently victim was transferred to Yishun Community Hospital and discharged on 21 August 2020. The victim was given 107 days of hospitalization leave from 8 July 2020 to 3 February 2021.

12     At the time of accident, it was raining, the road surface was wet, traffic volume was light and visibility was clear.

## Sentencing

### Prescribed Penalty

13     The prescribed penalty for an offence of driving without due care and attention and causing hurt under s 65(1)(_a_) punishable under s 65(4)(_a_) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”) is fine not exceeding $2,500 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding 12 months or to both.

14     In addition, s 42(1) of the RTA provides that a court before which person convicted of an offence in connection with the driving of a motor vehicle, may in addition to the punishment provided for the offence, order him to be disqualified from holding or obtaining a driving licence for life or for any period as the court may think fit.

## Antecedents

15     The accused is untraced.

## Prosecution’s Submissions on Sentence

16     It was submitted that the that the accused’s culpability was low while the harm was moderate as the victim had suffered from two types of fractures and underwent surgical fixation for both these injuries. It was further submitted that the victim is also an elderly man and was given a substantial period of medical leave.

17     The Prosecution had also considered the fact that the accused had pleaded guilty, he had rendered immediate assistance to the victim and that there were no culpability increasing factors. Hence, it was the Prosecution’s position that a fine of at least $2,500 fine and 18 months’ disqualification was appropriate.

## Defence’s Submissions on Sentence

18     The Defence had sought the imposition of a fine of $1,500 and a disqualification period of less than 12 months. In support of their sentencing position, reference was made to a table of recent reported cases which were punishable under s 65(4)(_a_) of the RTA.

19     In the plea mitigation, the Defence had highlighted the following factors:

> (a)     the accused had rendered immediate assistance to the victim;

> (b)     his cooperation with the relevant authorities at the earliest possible juncture and his timeous plea of guilt;

> (c)     he is a law-abiding citizen with an unblemished driving record;

> (d)     a disqualification of less than 12 months is suitable given his low culpability, low likelihood of reoffending and the victim’s contribution to the accident being caused. Such a period of disqualification is suitable given the legislative purpose of Section 42 of the RTA.

20     The Defence had also set out the accused’s personal circumstances. It was highlighted that given that he relies entirely on his income as a taxi driver for a living, any disqualification order imposed on him will be financially crippling and will result in his family facing extreme financial pressures.

21     It was submitted that from the footage of his in-vehicle camera, it could be seen that the accused was in fact a conscientious driver. On the material day, he had driven at a slow speed. He stopped his vehicle at the relevant Stop lines and checked for traffic before he proceeded on. The incident arose out of a momentarily lapse of judgment and his own failure to see the victim.

22     It was further submitted that from the video as well as the victim’s own police report, the victim himself had also contributed to the incident as he was jaywalking at the material time when it was raining. The victim himself accepted that there was a traffic light that was located just 50 metres away but he had chosen not to cross the road at the traffic light out of convenience. It was the Defence’s case that the victim himself had also contributed to this incident by blatantly breaching the traffic rules.

23     It was the Defence’s case that the accused had managed to stop his vehicle almost immediately and had rendered assistance immediately. His ability to stop the taxi almost immediately showed the slow speed that he was travelling at. Furthermore, there was also no vehicle damage which also showed the low force of the impact.

24     It was also submitted that the level of harm was on the lower end of medium. The victim had no permanent disabilities or long-term effects caused to the victim from the injuries that he had suffered.

25     In respect of the disqualification order to be imposed, it was submitted that the High Court decision of _Kwan Weiguang v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 121</span> (“_Kwan Weiguang_”) was instructive. From this decision, it was submitted that the sentencing objectives of a disqualification order are punishment, protection of public and deterrence. It was further submitted that it can be seen from _Kwan Weiguang_ that the most important sentencing principle is the protection of the public. As such particular weight should be placed on the culpability of the offender, his driving records and all these would reflect how much of a danger he poses to the public.

26     In deciding upon the length of disqualification, the district court in _Public Prosecutor v Lim Hock Lai_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGDC 104</span> (“_Lim Hock Lai_”) at \[17\] provided that the disqualification order should increase in tandem with the severity of the offence. The severity of the offence is evaluated by (a) the harm caused by the offence – which includes actual and potential harm and (b) the accused’s culpability – which must be assessed in the light of the extent and manner of his involvement in the criminal act.

27     In the present case, it was accepted that the accused’s culpability was low and his driving records were rather clear. On the day itself, he ensured that the traffic was clear before proceeding to drive out, and so his lack of care or attention was only momentary and not representative of how he generally conducts himself while driving, and therefore a low disqualification for all classes would be sufficient.

28     It was highlighted that the accused was not the violent or aggressive motorist that s 42 of the RTA was enacted to address and he has not placed any unwarranted risk on members of the public at large. Given the above, it was submitted that a disqualification that was lower than 12 months would be sufficient and that it will be appropriate in the current case.

29     It was further submitted that the incident is a one-off unfortunate incident, that at best arose from a moment of carelessness and not from a habitual disregard of safety rules. As such, the Prosecution’s request for 18 months disqualification was manifestly disproportionate and excessive.

## Prosecution’s Reply

30     In response to the plea in mitigation, the Prosecution firstly submitted that whether or not the accused faces contractual or professional consequences from the disqualification order should not be relevant to the sentencing court.

31     Secondly, regarding the main point of contention which was the period of disqualification, it was submitted that even in the table of precedents that the Defence has submitted, none of the disqualification period actually goes below the period of 12 months.

32     According to the Prosecution, it was highlighted by the Defence that the accused is a competent driver and this should not necessitate the retake of the test of competence. However, it was the Prosecution’s case that the driving test is not only to test whether one is competent, but it is also to test whether one is a safe driver. Based on this incident, the accused has demonstrated that he is not a safe driver; he was careless.

## Decision on sentence

### Sentencing approach

33     S 65(1) of the RTA encapsulates the primary offence of driving without due care or reasonable consideration for other persons using the road. The subsequent subsections from ss 65(2) to 65(4) are the penalty prescribing provisions, each tiered according to the degree of hurt caused and for s 65(5), for any other case of non-personal injury or potential harm.

#### Irresponsible driving under the Road Traffic Act

34     The present offence of driving without due care and attention under s 65(1)(_a_) of the RTA was enacted on 1 November 2019, following the passing of the Road Traffic (Amendment) Act 2019 (Act 19 of 2019). The Amendment Act arose out of a review of the RTA and it aimed to provide stronger deterrence against irresponsible driving, according to the explanation presented by the Second Minister for Home Affairs, Mrs Josephine Teo (the “Minister”) to Parliament on 8 July 2019 (_Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Official Report_ (8 July 2019), vol 94). The Minister’s explanation is set out below:

> I will start with our enhanced approach towards irresponsible driving offences. Today, irresponsible driving offences are prosecuted in two ways. One way is under the Penal Code, for Rash Act and Negligent Act. Another way is under the RTA, for Reckless or Dangerous Driving, and Driving without Due Care or Reasonable Consideration. The penalties differ.

> For better clarity and consistency, we propose to consolidate irresponsible driving offences under the RTA. We will also streamline the offences into two classes: the first category is Reckless or Dangerous Driving, which I will refer to as Dangerous Driving in the rest of the speech. The second category is Driving without Due Care or Reasonable Consideration, which I will refer to as Careless Driving. 

> The definitions of Dangerous Driving and Careless Driving are currently in the RTA. We will maintain the current definitions.

> Dangerous Driving is more serious than Careless Driving. The two can be differentiated, on a case-by-case basis. The three main considerations, among others, are as follows.

> First, whether the manner of driving predictably puts other road users at risk and cause other road users to be unable to react in time. Examples of driving that are considered as dangerous, as opposed to careless, include swerving across lanes suddenly and without warning, driving against the flow of traffic and speeding.

> Second, whether the motorist had driven, even though he should have known he was not in a condition to drive safely. Examples of behaviour that are considered dangerous include using mobile devices while driving and failing to use visual aids such as spectacles even though he is seriously short-sighted.

> Third, whether the road situation required the motorist to take extra care but he did not. Examples include when he is approaching a zebra crossing, or a junction where other road users have the right of way.

> When determining the punishment, we will look at the circumstances under which the offence is committed. The threshold for Dangerous Driving is higher than Careless Driving; so too the penalties. 

> Besides looking at the circumstances of the offence, our enhanced approach will also consider the level of harm caused. If the motorist causes more harm, the level of punishment will be higher. 

> There will be four levels of harm: Death, Grievous Hurt, Hurt and Endangering Life. Such tiering of harm is not new in our laws – the Penal Code already has it. 

> To summarise, we will enhance our overall approach to penalise irresponsible driving depending on: (a) the circumstances of the offence – whether it constitutes Dangerous Driving or Careless Driving; and (b) the level of harm caused – whether they result in Death, Grievous Hurt, Hurt, or Endangering Life. 

35     As at the date of my decision, there is no existing sentencing framework enunciated by the High Court for an offence driving without due care and attention and causing hurt punishable under s 65(4)(_a_) of the RTA. There is however a sentencing framework for an offence of driving without due care and attention and causing grievous hurt punishable under s 65(3)(_a_) of the RTA recently prescribed by Vincent Hoong J (“_Hoong J_”) in _Sue Chang (Xu Zheng) v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 176</span> (“_Sue Chang_”). In that case, Hoong J had dismissed the appeal and prescribed the following sentencing framework for offences under section 65(3)(_a_) of the RTA where the offender has claimed trial.

![](data:image;base64,)

36     In _Sue Chang_, Hoong J made to two key observations at \[38\] to \[40\] in relation to the RTA amendments in the context of careless or inconsiderate driving. Firstly, as observed by Sundaresh Menon CJ (“Menon CJ”) in _Wu Zhi Yong v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2021\] SGHC 261</span> (“_Wu Zhi Yong_”) at \[15\] (albeit in the related context of s 64 of the RTA), the Amendment Act envisaged a new scheme of penalties for careless or inconsiderate driving in a tiered structure calibrated according to the degree of hurt caused. This is codified in the RTA as ss 65(2) to 65(5). The maximum punishments which may be imposed for each category of harm increase concomitantly with the seriousness of the harm caused; this translates into wider ranges of punishments where more serious harm is occasioned. For instance, where death is caused, s 65(2)(_a_) provides that a first-time offender is liable to a fine not exceeding $10,000 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding three years or to both. In contrast, the residual category (where no actual physical harm is caused, but which includes cases of non-personal injury or potential harm) captured in s 65(5)(_a_) provides that a first-time offender is liable to a fine not exceeding $1,500 or to imprisonment for a term not exceeding six months or to both. By tiering the punishment provisions in accordance with the type of harm suffered, Parliament has given clear expression to the need to give explicit consideration to the _outcomes_ that result from instances of careless or inconsiderate driving. This is a stark departure from the structure of s 65 of the pre-2019 RTA, where there was a single range of punishment with no differentiation based on the type and/or degree of harm caused.

37     Secondly, while Parliament has retained the distinction between reckless or dangerous driving under s 64 of the RTA and careless or inconsiderate driving under s 65 of the RTA, this distinction has been made more pronounced through the refining of the punishment provisions. These two provisions reflect the differing circumstances under which an irresponsible driving offence can occur. As can be seen from the Second Minister for Home Affairs, Mrs Josephine Teo’s speech at \[36\], the former offence is regarded as being more serious than the latter, reflecting primarily the differing levels of culpability of the offenders. Accordingly, the current architecture of the RTA concerning irresponsible driving offences tiers the punishment provisions according to _both_ harm and culpability, not dissimilar to the Penal Code.

38     At \[65\] of his judgment, Justice Hoong opined that the most suitable sentencing approach to adopt in respect of offences under s 65(3)(_a_) of the RTA is the two-stage, five-step sentencing framework laid down by Menon CJ in _Logachev Vladislav v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 4 SLR 609</span> at \[75\](“_Logachev_\-hybrid approach”). At \[84\] to \[108\] of his judgment, Hoong J had set out the five steps to be taken namely:

> (a)     The _first step_ is to identify the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of culpability of the offender. The harm caused by the offence may be categorised into three levels of increasing severity: low, moderate and serious. Likewise, the offender’s culpability may be categorised into three levels: low, moderate and high. The non-exhaustive list of factors within the broad categories of harm and culpability which fashion the two axes of the matrix are:

>> (1)        _Factors going to harm_

>> The degree of harm caused would generally refer to the nature and degree of the grievous bodily injury caused to the victim(s): see _Tang Ling Lee v PP_ <span class="citation">\[2018\] 4 SLR 813</span> at \[25\] (“_Tang Ling Lee_”). The levels of harm can be divided based on the severity of the grievous hurt suffered as follows:

>>> (i)        Low: The hurt caused can be managed with conservative treatment, with no or short periods of hospitalisation and/or medical leave. The harm occasioned would typically involve minor fractures/dislocation at less vulnerable parts of the body.

>>> (ii)        Moderate: The injuries are of a more permanent nature and/or involve more complex fractures/dislocation which necessitate some surgical procedures with a moderate period of hospitalisation and/or medical leave.

>>> (iii)        Serious: The injuries are of a very serious or permanent nature and/or necessitate significant surgical procedures. The victim’s daily living is usually permanently and severely affected. This includes injuries resulting in loss of limb, sight, hearing, member or other major bodily functions or paralysis.

> In addition, there are two other factors which may contribute to the severity of the harm caused, namely: (a) property damage; and (b) potential harm. These factors are to be considered in tandem with the above descriptions of each level of harm.

>> (2)        _Factors going to culpability_

>>> This can be measured based on the following factors:

>>>> (a)       Circumstances which required the offender to exercise extra care or consideration. Some examples of these circumstances include where the offender drives: (i) within a school or residential zone; (ii) a heavy vehicle that is more difficult to control and requires a quicker reaction time; or (iii) in poor road conditions (_eg_, heavy rain or heavy traffic);

>>>> (b)       The manner of driving. Under this factor, it is apposite to consider any dangerous driving behaviour exhibited by the offender. This would include, for example, driving against the flow of traffic, speeding, sleepy driving, drink-driving, driving while under the influence of drugs, driving while using a mobile phone, flouting traffic rules, or “hell-riding” situations: see _Tang Ling Lee_ at \[28\]. In addition, considerations pertaining to the duration of the offender’s inattention (_eg_, momentary or prolonged/sustained), the avoidability of the offender’s distraction or the reasonableness of the offender’s misjudgment are also relevant;

>>>> (c)       The offender’s conduct following the offence. An offender’s conduct that is “belligerent or violent” upon arrest would constitute an aggravating factor: see _Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> (“_Suse Nathen_”) at \[32\]. Where the offender fails to stop in an attempt to evade arrest or to avoid apprehension by the authorities, this should also weigh against him: see _Public Prosecutor v Lee Meng Soon_ <span class="citation">\[2007\] 4 SLR(R) 240</span> at \[33\].

> (b)     The _second step_ is to identify the applicable indicative sentencing range in the sentencing matrix. Any term of imprisonment imposed may be accompanied by a fine of up to $5,000, if appropriate as this is explicitly provided for in s 65(3)(_a_) of the RTA. The sentencing judge should be alive to possibility of imposing such a combination of punishments in order to properly take into account the full sentencing range prescribed by Parliament. Hoong J opined that Parliament has stressed the importance of both harm and culpability and did not suggest that one factor should be given more weight in the sentencing analysis than the other. He emphasized that the proposed sentencing framework and the corresponding indicative ranges set out above are concerned solely with section 65(3)(_a_) of the RTA.

> (c)     The _third step_ is to identify the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range. This is to be informed by the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of the offender’s culpability.

> (d)     The _fourth step_ is to make adjustments to the starting point where necessary to take into account the offender-specific aggravating and mitigating factors: see _Ng Kean Meng Terence v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2017\] 2 SLR 449</span> (“_Terence Ng”)_ at \[62\]-\[71\].

> (e)     The _fifth step_ is to make further adjustments to take into account the totality principle. This step is relevant only where an offender is faced with multiple charges. It requires the court to consider the need to make further adjustments to the individual sentences for each charge to take into account the totality principle. The totality principle has been expressed in _Mohamed Shouffee bin Adam v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 2 SLR 998</span> at \[54\] and \[57\] as comprising two limbs. The first limb examines whether the aggregate sentence is substantially above the _normal_ level of sentences for the most serious of the individual offences committed. The second limb considers whether the effect of the sentence on the offender is crushing and not in keeping with his past record and his future prospects.

39     Although the present case concerns a charge of driving without due care and attention and causing hurt, as both statutory provisions relate to the prescribed penalties for irresponsible driving under s 65(1), I was of the view the observations as well as the sentencing approach set out by Hoong J provides some useful guidance on how an offence punishable under s 65(4)(_a_) of the RTA should be dealt with.

#### The sentence

40     I now turn to the facts of the present case and the application of the above sentencing framework.

41     The _first step_ is to identify the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of culpability of the offender. In the present case, I agreed with the Prosecution that the level of harm was within the moderate range in view of the two types of fractures, the surgical fixation he underwent for both these injuries, his length of hospitalisation as well as his substantial period of medical leave.

42     I was mindful that the victim suffered a left hip intertrochanteric fracture, a vulnerable part of the body and a left knee tibia plateau fracture. He subsequently underwent surgical fixation of his left hip as well as his left proximal tibia. He was hospitalised for 15 days from 8 July 2020 to 23 July 2020 and subsequently transferred to Yishun Community Hospital and discharged on 21 August 2020 (after 30 days). He was given 107 days of hospitalization leave from 8 July 2020 to 3 February 2021. Hence, in view of these factors, I disagreed with the Defence’s characterisation of the harm caused as being at the lower end of medium/moderate. As for the accused’s level of culpability, I agreed with the Prosecution and the Defence that it was low as the accident occurred out of a momentary lapse of attention when he failed to keep a proper lookout ahead and collided into the victim as he made the right turn.

43     The _second step_ is to identify the applicable indicative sentencing range in the sentencing matrix. Any term of imprisonment imposed may be accompanied by a fine of up to $2,500, if appropriate as this is explicitly provided for in s 65(4)(_a_) of the RTA. The sentencing judge should be alive to possibility of imposing such a combination of punishments in order to properly take into account the full sentencing range prescribed by Parliament. Based on the _Sue Chang_ sentencing framework where the level of culpability is low and the harm moderate, the appropriate range of sentence would be a fine or a custodial sentence. In the present case, I agreed with the Prosecution and the Defence that the custodial threshold had not been crossed. In view of the seriousness of the harm caused which resulted in the victim suffering two types of fractures, the surgical fixation he underwent for both these injuries, his lengthy period of hospitalisation as well as his substantial period of medical leave I was of the view that the fine imposed should be on the upper range.

44     The _third step_ is to identify the appropriate starting point within the indicative sentencing range. This is to be informed by the level of harm caused by the offence and the level of the offender’s culpability. In the present case, in view of the degree of harm caused, I was of the view that the starting point should be the maximum fine of $2,500.

45     The _fourth step_ is to make adjustments to the starting point where necessary to take into account the offender-specific aggravating and mitigating factors. In the present case, I considered the fact that the accused had pleaded guilty to the charge, he had no prior antecedents, he had rendered immediate assistance to the victim and had cooperated with the authorities. I further considered that there were no culpability enhancing factors in the present case. Accordingly, I was of the view that a downward calibration of the maximum fine to $2,000 was warranted in view of these mitigating factors.

46     I disagreed with the Defence’s position that a fine of $1,500 was appropriate in view of the seriousness of the harm caused as the victim suffered two types of fractures which required surgical fixation and he was given a substantial period of hospitalisation leave to aid in his recovery. I did not place any weight to the Defence’s submissions on his personal circumstances as a sole breadwinner and the extreme financial pressures his family would face. It is trite that financial difficulties are not to be regarded as mitigating factors, save for exceptional circumstances: see _Lai Oei Mui Jenny v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[1993\] 2 SLR(R) 406</span> at \[10\].

47     The _fifth step_ was not applicable in the present case as the accused faced a single charge.

#### Disqualification order

48     In deciding on the appropriate period of disqualification, I was mindful that the disqualification order and the sentence imposed are not mutually compensatory; an increase in the quantum of the fine imposed should not be taken to mandate the imposition of a reduced period of disqualification than would otherwise have been ordered: _Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> at \[13\].

49     In determining the appropriate length of the disqualification order, I was guided by the approach in the recent case of _Kwan Weiguang v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2022\] SGHC 121</span> (“_Kwan_”). Although Aedit Abdullah J dealt with an appeal against a disqualification order of 15 months that was imposed on the appellant for an offence of dangerous driving under s 64(1) and punishable under s 64(2C)(_a_) of the RTA, the factors considered are relevant to the present case. He held at \[59\] and \[61\] that the objective of the disqualification order is as follow:

> A driving disqualification order combines three sentencing objectives: punishment, protection of the public and deterrence (_Edwin s/o Suse Nathen v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2013\] 4 SLR 1139</span> (“_Edwin Nathen_”) at \[13\]). Often, due to the limited range of fines in the punishment provision, the impact of a disqualification order is likely to be felt much more acutely than any marginal increase in the quantum of the fine (see Edwin Nathen at \[13\])…

> 61    A disqualification order also serves to remove the privilege to drive from those who have abused it, and this also reinforces the notion of shared usage of the roads. It must be remembered that driving is an inherently dangerous activity. The licence to drive is a privilege accorded to persons who, through a series of properly administered tests, have demonstrated that they are capable of meeting the standards expected of a reasonably competent driver (_Jali bin Mohd Yunos v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2014\] 4 SLR 1059</span> at \[36\]). The former Minister for Home Affairs, Prof S Jayakumar, had expressed the following view which reinforces this notion (see Singapore Parliamentary Debates, Official Report (28 March 1990) vol 55 at col 960): “… we must get every driver in Singapore to note that when he is issued a licence, it is in fact a very special privilege and it is granted on condition that he drives in a responsible manner bearing in mind the interest of others.”

50     In _Kwan_ at \[65\] to \[71\], the relevant and material factors when determining the period of disqualification are:

> (a)     Circumstances of the commission of the offence;

> (b)     Continued ability to drive and attitude towards other road users.

51     In the present case, the accused had failed to keep a proper lookout ahead and collided onto the victim’s left side. This was despite the fact that the victim, an elderly man can be seen standing on the accused’s right side and the victim was waiting in the middle of the road when the accused’s taxi was at the Stop line. The impact caused the victim’s head and body to hit the bonnet and the victim fell to the ground. The victim suffered a left hip intertrochanteric fracture which is at a vulnerable part of the body and a left knee tibia plateau fracture.

52     In addition, there was a fair degree of potential harm, considering the conditions at the material time. Although the traffic volume was described in the Statement of Facts as light, it was evident from the footage that the road traffic was not negligible. The victim can be seen standing on the accused’s right side and the victim was waiting in the middle of the road for the road to be clear before progressively crossing each lane of the road towards Block 239 of Yishun Ring Road. The offence occurred at about at about 3.02pm along Yishun Ring Road towards Yishun Avenue 2 when there was still some traffic, and this is unlike the situation in _Neo Chuan Sheng v Public Prosecutor_ <span class="citation">\[2020\] SGHC 97</span> where the offence was committed at about 2.10am when no vehicles or pedestrians would be expected to be on the road. It is foreseeable that the changing of lanes as he made the right turn after exiting the carpark onto the main road and the sudden braking of the taxi by the accused to stop the taxi after he collided into the victim could have caused a collision with other vehicles travelling along Yishun Ring Road. This risk was accentuated by the fact that it would be harder for the accused to control his taxi given that it was drizzling and the road surface was wet.

53     It was clear that in the present case it was within the public’s interest to remove such a driver from the roads for a substantial period of time. Based on the above factors, a disqualification period of less than 12 months sought by the Defence would be wholly inappropriate in the circumstances. Under such circumstances, a disqualification period of higher than 12 months was warranted. Although the Prosecution has sought a disqualification period of 18 months, in my view as the victim was jaywalking even though there was a traffic light located just 50 metres away but had chosen not to cross the road at the traffic light out of convenience a downward calibration of the proposed disqualification period was appropriate.

54     In my view, taking all the above circumstances into account, a disqualification period of fifteen months for all classes of vehicles was appropriate to fulfil the objectives of punishment, the protection of the public and deterrence.

55     All things considered, I was of the view that the fine of $2,000 and disqualification from holding or obtaining all classes of driving licences for a period of fifteen months in respect of DAC 921123-2021 was just and appropriate in the circumstances.
